## Brand & Pricing Strategy

Four operating principles (PokeNE, May 2026). Apply on every pricing, restock, or buyback question.

### 1. Price at replacement cost, not historical cost

When ~30-40% sold through, check current supplier/lot replacement cost. If it rose, reprice remaining stock to match before running out. Profit must cover *next* restock, not just original purchase.

- Asian sealed: check supplier rate at 30% sell-through, reprice if moved.
- English sealed: check wholesaler/distributor rate, reprice if market moved.
- Slabs (buyback-sourced): check TCGPlayer + eBay sold comps, reprice if comps moved.

### 2. Price at market, never undercut

HOKO10 is customer acquisition; day-to-day pricing is at market. Moat = honest grading + same-day dispatch + buybacks + trust, not low price. Bigger sellers can always go lower on volume.

### 3. Collection buybacks: rigid, professional, copy-paste

Pay 75-80% of fair market value. Use the fixed intake template every time — never freeball.

**Non-negotiables:**
- What we buy: factory-sealed TCG + PSA/BGS/CGC slabs. Nothing else.
- Where we meet: bank branch / storage unit, business hours. No home pickups.
- Quote = 48-hour validity, after photo + typed list received.
- Payment = bank transfer on the day. No PayPal, no cash, no instalments.

Intake email template lives in the cloud repo at `templates/collection-buyback-intake.md` — copy-paste every time, only customise the recipient's name. Stern = signals professional.

### 4. Be platform-agnostic — own the brand

eBay/Whatnot/TCGPlayer/conventions are channels, not the business. Every parcel, caption, stream, DM reinforces the brand identity (`hokocollectables.com`, `@hokocollectables`, "Collector first. Seller second.") so the audience follows when channels change.

